# CSS and Tailwind (Rails)

## Rails Owns the Pipeline

Use **Tailwind the Rails way**: the **`tailwindcss-rails`** gem and the default asset story (**Propshaft** or **Sprockets** — whatever the app uses). The CSS entrypoint lives under **`app/assets`** (e.g. `app/assets/tailwind/application.css` or `app/assets/stylesheets/application.tailwind.css` depending on setup). **Do not** scatter `@tailwind` directives across arbitrary ERB files — global layers belong in the **one** stylesheet the build compiles.

Canonical procedural detail: **`skills/writing-css-tailwind/references/patterns.md`**. **Where** classes sit in markup (partials, `class_names`, helpers) stays in **`rules/views.mdc`** and **`skills/writing-views`**.

## Tailwind v3 vs v4

**Do not mix documentation.** v3 uses **`tailwind.config.js`** (JS config). v4 is often **CSS-first** (`@import "tailwindcss"`, theme in CSS). Identify which stack the project uses before editing config or copy-pasting snippets from the web.

## Utility-First, Rails-Structured

- **Utilities on elements** — default. Repetition is managed with **partials** and **helpers**, not premature abstraction.
- **Partials** = markup + structure reuse; **helpers** = `class_names` and small composed tags; **ViewComponent** = optional when a partial + helper is insufficient (repeated subtree, clear API, tests) — not “everything is a component.”
- **No parallel design system in JS** — no CSS-in-JS or client theme layers for ordinary Hotwire-first UI. Stimulus toggles **classes** or **`data-*`** hooks.

## @apply

**Rare.** Acceptable for narrow glue (e.g. prose plugin, third-party widgets). **Not** a second component framework — if `@apply` proliferates, extract partials and helpers instead. See **`skills/writing-css-tailwind/references/patterns.md`** § @apply.

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Instead |
|-------------|---------|
| Token layers / bespoke naming that duplicates Tailwind’s scale without team payoff | Tailwind utilities + partials; extend theme when truly shared |
| CSS-in-JS or component-library styling as the primary pattern for ERB + Hotwire apps | Utilities in templates; Stimulus toggles classes |
| `@apply` everywhere | Partials and helper-returned class strings |
| Giant class strings **only** in Ruby as the default API | Visible markup in ERB; helpers for real repetition |
| Global CSS that assumes full page reload only, breaking Turbo morphing / frames | Test navigations and frame updates; avoid layout CSS that fights Turbo |
| Pasting v3 `tailwind.config.js` patterns into a v4 CSS-first project (or the reverse) | Match the project’s actual major version |
| Extra JS bundler complexity “because React did it” when importmap + Stimulus is the standard | One clear JS story; **`rules/javascript.mdc`** |

